entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: why

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: sometimes i feel like i do not fit into the crowd so it is better just sometimes to be more quiet and view everything instead of you know going in and actively pursue things

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: what do you do to relax

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably listen to music and spend time with my dogs

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: cool what are some things that make you really mad

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably people being insensitive not very very nice to me or seeing injustices or i think that is about it

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: yeah how are you at controlling your temper

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: pretty good you know sometimes

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: when was the last time you argued with someone and what was it about

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably couple of days ago one of my friends was saying that they were making a coent about how i am and i got kind of upset about that

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how close are you to them

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: pretty close

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how do you know them

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: my best friend so i oh just one of my friends

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: okay what do you do when you are annoyed

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i kind of am quiet about it and when a person pushes me to a certain point that is when i overreact usually

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how hard is that

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: it is pretty hard i rather the person notice that i am kinda getting withdrawn and actively engage in me instead of getting it to the point where it is like it it comes to a point where it blows out of proportion

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: yeah i understand what is one of your most memorable experiences

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably spending time with my family in new york

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: that is good how would your best friend describe you

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably i guess loyal sensitive i do not know it is kind of hard it is a hard question

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: okay have you ever served in the military

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: no

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: have you ever been diagnosed with ptsd

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: no

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: have you been diagnosed with depression

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: yes

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how long ago were you diagnosed

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: gosh i think probably nineteen ninety seven so a long time ago

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: what got you to seek help

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i am just during that time i was just going through a lot of issues and i was feeling unsafe to myself so i ended up going to the doctor to kinda get meds and have therapy and stuff

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: do you still go to therapy now

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: not currently i i did about like six months ago

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: why did you stop

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i just felt the therapist was not really helping me i felt we kept on talking about the same things over and over and xxx she was not really challenging me and i have been in therapy for a really long time so i just knew it was a change

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: do you feel like therapy is useful

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: yes i do actually when i feel connected to a therapist and when i feel like it is a really great way for me to talk about what i am going through so yes i do

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: what sort of changes have you noticed since you have been going to therapy

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i am better at describing my emotions and feelings i think the biggest thing is when i am in situations eh i can see myself reacting one way and i take a step back and see how i can react normally almost in a way also i tend to take a lot of my emotions and feelings and kind of bury them and make them feel like really bad about myself so it is nice to talk to someone that is not judging that does not really tell me like you know they tell me it is o okay basically

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: that is good what were your symptoms

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: feeling hopeless all the time not having you know enough energy to do things i used to like i had a little bit of concentration issues having weird disturbing thoughts sometimes just pop into my mind and just overall just feeling kinda cry about life

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: are they triggered by something

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: sometimes they are at like random moments that if there is like a problem with like my interpersonal life or something like that or if i sometimes even seeing something on television like sometimes that affects me

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how do you cope with them

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: listening to music or trying to distract myself trying like my therapist told me for the longest time to journal to record things

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: okay how easy is it for you to get a good night is sleep

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: some days it is great some days it is not more recently it is been a little bit more difficult

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: why

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i do not know why i have like a lot of thoughts on my mind at night so i tend not to sleep very well and i wake up quite frequently during the night

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: what are you like when you do not sleep well

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: very groggy in the morning and that is about it like during the day i tend to yawn a lot and my friends always are like oh why are you yawning so much are you disinterested in what we are doing and then trying to tell them it is not that at all

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: okay when was the last time you felt really happy

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: probably christmas time when i was with my family

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how did you feel in that moment how did you feel in that moment

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: just really happy and feeling like everything was alright in my life having a good sense of like where i was at that moment being present with myself

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: okay what are you most proud of in your life

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i do not know that is a good question probably my previous job and my employment i worked really well with kids so i did a great job at that i was a researcher at a hospital and i helped a lot of kids out for about six years so seven years

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: wow that sounds interesting

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: yeah it was awesome

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: how did you decide to do that

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: i was really kind of like reading people and so i decided to major in psychology so and then i went a worked in a mental health facility and did research with them with with drugs and depression and things like that so it found like a good niche for me

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: that is great okay i think i have asked everything i need to

entries.speaker: participant
entries.text: okay

entries.speaker: ellie
entries.text: thanks for sharing your thoughts with me

entries.speaker: participant
